===subject:Reply to Chris
===from:Robert Napier
===date:Mon Apr 14 10:17:04 2003
===message:Chris, your right that we don’t swear an oath to the President, but the position is our commander and chief and with that title comes a certain amount of respect. Just like we respect our boss, police officers, parents, spouses, and etc. We may never agree with their viewpoints, but we tend to still show them a certain amount of respect. The only difference is that the President is our voice and leadership to the other parts of the world. I love the fact that I live in democracy were I can make comments about the elected officials, but I never lose sight in knowing that I have this freedom because I live in America. In saying that I do think that it is un-America not to respect your President or any elected officials, because I know that have the right to change who ever is in power come next election cycle. Anyone can be rude and disrespectful, but it takes an individual that has a certain of class and dignity to respond in a thoughtful and intelligent manner. 
=========yorg=========
